node.text: In-car video of me running 208.791 mph to set a record at El Mirage Dry Lake!  There’s SO much to see, you’re gonna have to run through it a few times. 1) Watch through the middle of the windshield to see how much the tail wags down the track. 2) Notice, from start to finish, how much dust builds up in the car. 3) Watch the tach needle jump as the tires break loose at the top of First and again at the top of Second, and I pedal it to recover. 4) At the end of the run, watch my hand go to the parachute, then back to the shifter, then back to the chute. Watch the tach at the same time. We had too high of a gear in the car, and at 200 mph I had to decide if I was going to leave the trans in Third across the finish line or if I’d shift. I had decided to stay in Third and put my hand on the chute, but then the engine hit the rev limiter at 8,200 rpm and I reached to shift—but the engine nosing over upset the car and kicked the rear sideways, so I immediately snatched the chute to pull the car straight.  5) From clutch-out to pulling the parachute is 34 seconds.  6) Look carefully and you’ll see the finish line marker pass by right as I pull the parachute. I deploy the chute early so that it blossoms immediately after I’m through the timing trap. Wait too long and you’re off the end of the track. 7) After I turn off, I’m super chill at like 150 mph putting the chute cable back. When strapped in the car, I can’t see the chute handle or any switches.  8) At the end, SCTA officials Rick Head and Lee Kennedy have rolled to a stop alongside me and tell me my time. Rick asks if I had permission to go that fast, which I did. 9) Going back to the start, note SCTA officials Nick Arias III and Jill Iverson sending me off. You’ll see that the push truck has me already moving when I put the car in First and take off. I drove away from the push truck sooner than I would at Bonneville because the El Mirage track is so much shorter so I need to start accelerating hard as soon as I can. 10) Buy a shirt! Link in my profile.

node.text: Tucson Dragway October 1-2! Come on down to Tucson for the cheapest cars and the biggest fun! We will have a cruise from the Los Angeles area on Friday, a test and tune Friday night, then bonfire and beers. On Saturday it’s low-buck drags, a car show, burnout/donut box, and open grudge racing. I’ll definitely be there with some of my cars, and both Finnegan and Dulcich have tentatively said they’d like too be there. Stay tuned for details by following @tucsondragway. Want to sponsor, then contact @joesebergandio. Note that MotorTrend is not affiliated with this event. Will you be at #ducttapedrags?

node.text: Here’s a test of the switch panel on the dash of my F-Rod, a Model A drag race car. NOTE: in the video I was confused about the amp draw on the fourth toggle. Easy answer: the wires I’d twisted together temporarily for the test had come apart. The correct data for all four switches is .434 amps. Even with the alternator putting out 14-plus volts, these switches won’t even be carrying 3/4 of an amp.

node.text: For sale! Who remembers my ‘32 Ford “Roaster” from Hot Rod Mag circa 2004? Years ago I sold it to Keith and Tonya Turk, and now they are ready to let it go. It only has about 500 miles on it since it was first finished. I built it with inspiration from the Phil Cool car (though it has always needed bigger rear tires). It’s an Australian Deuce Customs fiberglass body on a TCI frame. It has a 500hp 454 with dual quads, a TKO five-speed stick, and a Currie 9-inch with 3.50s. The paint is House of Kolor Tangelo Pearl and it has a Lobek chopped windshield. The interior is fresh and retro with pleats and a ‘58 Impala wheel, Limeworks column, trad column drop, and SoCal dash insert with Auto Meter gauges. Lots of neat stuff like a US radiator, aluminum pump, Cal Custom covers, O’Brien Truckers air cleaner, ‘50 Pontiac taillights, SoCal bullnose and cowl trim, etc. It’s a cool car that’s scary fast. You should get it. Keith is currently fiddling with a few small fixes from the car sitting, and is asking $32k. It’s in southern Alabama. Contact @keithturk200

node.text: NO, the Hemi Gremmie will never do wheelies. I’m surprised by the number of people who comment about the car and expect that it will do easy wheelstands. Consider that it has an 800-pound, iron-head Hemi with at least half the engine hanging in front of the axle. That does not add up to wheelies. The engine makes about 530 hp and the rear gear is 3.50–also not a wheelie combo. This thing is not intended for anything but cruising and huge burnouts and ridiculous looks. In other words…it’s a Street Freak. And it does its job well. Seen the episode yet? #streetfreak #notagasser

node.text: Today I sort of want this. It’s a ‘41 Ford sedan powered by a Ford 300ci inline six, and also has a C6, 9-inch, and Camaro clip. Apparently it has raced La Carrera Panamericana. If you don’t know the history of that road race, look it up. It dates back to 1950-1954, after which they cancelled it because too many people were killed, even by ‘50s standards. It came back some time in the ‘90s, leading to cars like this. The ‘41 is pretty Roadkilled, but I think I could tidy it up and have a lot of fun with it. #lacarrerapanamericana

node.text: $70,000???? Man, I’m considering a replacement for my ‘99 Dodge and have been looking at new and used trucks from the past 10 years and I have to say there is not a single one I want to own. Not only are prices OUTRAGEOUS, even for used stuff, but how come they are all so ugly? It’s like a study in nose-heavy oversized grilles, and tires that are way too small for the wheelwells. And the bodies are just too big. Plus there’s too much technology. And I was shocked to learn you can buy a full-size truck with a FOUR CYLINDER. I know I’m a dinosaur and out of touch, but what happened to the days of a 10-year-old used truck for $3500? I guess I’ll be working on fixing the death wobble on my 22-year-old Dodge after all.
